<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900705-0073</DOCNO><DOCID>900705-0073.</DOCID><HL>   Two Men Get Prison Terms   For Falsifying Test Results</HL><DATE>07/05/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Two men were sentenced after pleadingguilty in April to a long-running scam involving falsifiedtest results on millions of nuts and bolts designed to fastenparts in aircraft engines.   Norman McHaffie, president of the now-defunct defensecontractor McHaffie Inc. of Sylmar, Calif., was sentenced tothree years in prison and three years' probation and wasfined $750,000. James Hicks, an employee, was sentenced toone and a half years in prison and two years' probation, andthe company was fined $750,000.</LP><TEXT>   A third defendant, former shop floor manager WilliamWhitham, was sentenced June 18 to 20 weekends in prison,three years' probation and 150 hours of community serviceafter pleading guilty.   The government accused the men of participating in a10-year scheme beginning in 1979 that involved more than4,000 government and commercial contracts. According to thegovernment's investigation, the company did not conductPentagon-mandated tests on the products, but went to greatlengths to falsify results and otherwise mask the fraud.</TEXT></DOC>